SIMPLE: hammer
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hammer
<hw>Ham"mer</hw> <pr>(h⟦acr⟧m"m⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>hamer</ets>, AS. <ets>hamer</ets>, <ets>hamor</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>hamer</ets>, G. & Dan. <ets>hammer</ets>, Sw. <ets>hammare</ets>,
Icel. <ets>hamarr</ets>, hammer, crag, and perh. to Gr.
<grk>'a`kmwn</grk> anvil, Skr. <ets>a⟦cced⟧man</ets> stone.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>An instrument for driving nails, beating metals, and
the like, consisting of a head, usually of steel or iron, fixed
crosswise to a handle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With busy <qex>hammers</qex> closing rivets up.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Something which in form or action resembles the
common hammer</def>; as: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>That part of a clock which
strikes upon the bell to indicate the hour.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The
padded mallet of a piano, which strikes the wires, to produce the
tones.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The malleus.</def> See
under <er>Ear</er>. <sd>(d)</sd> <fld>(Gun.)</fld> <def>That part of a
gunlock which strikes the percussion cap, or firing pin; the cock;
formerly, however, a piece of steel covering the pan of a flintlock
musket and struck by the flint of the cock to ignite the priming.</def>
<sd>(e)</sd> <def>Also, a person or thing that smites or shatters;
<as>as, St. Augustine was the <ex>hammer</ex> of
heresies.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He met the stern legionaries [of Rome] who had been the
⟦ldquo⟧massive iron <qex>hammers</qex>⟦rdquo⟧ of the whole earth.</q>
<rj><qau>J. H. Newman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Athletics)</fld> <def>A spherical weight attached
to a flexible handle and hurled from a mark or ring. The weight of head
and handle is usually not less than 16 pounds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Atmospheric hammer</b></col>, <cd>a dead-stroke hammer in
which the spring is formed by confined air.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Drop
hammer</b></col>, <col><b>Face hammer</b></col>, etc.</mcol> <cd>See
under <er>Drop</er>, <er>Face</er>, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Hammer
fish</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Hammerhead</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Hammer
hardening</b></col>, <cd>the process of hardening metal by hammering it
when cold.</cd> -- <col><b>Hammer shell</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>,
<cd>any species of <gen>Malleus</gen>, a genus of marine bivalve shells,
allied to the pearl oysters, having the wings narrow and elongated, so
as to give them a hammer-shaped outline; -- called also <altname>hammer
oyster</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>To bring to the hammer</b></col>,
<cd>to put up at auction.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hammer</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hammer
<hw>Ham"mer</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Hammered</conjf> <pr>(-m⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Hammering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To beat
with a hammer; to beat with heavy blows; <as>as, to <ex>hammer</ex>
iron</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To form or forge with a hammer; to shape by
beating.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Hammered</xex> money.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To form in the mind; to shape by hard intellectual
labor; -- usually with <xex>out</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who was <qex>hammering</qex> out a penny dialogue.</q>
<rj><qau>Jeffry.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hammer</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hammer
<hw>Ham"mer</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be busy forming
anything; to labor hard as if shaping something with a hammer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whereon this month I have been <qex>hammering</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To strike repeated blows, literally or
figuratively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Blood and revenge are <qex>hammering</qex> in my head.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hammerable</ent>⟦br⟧
